# =============================================================================
# vibe-land environment configuration
# =============================================================================
#
# The production stack has three processes:
#
#   1. Rust game server  — authoritative simulation + netcode
#        * HTTP/WS on BIND_ADDR  (session-config, /ws/, /healthz)
#        * WebTransport on WT_BIND_ADDR  (UDP/QUIC, NOT proxyable by nginx)
#
#   2. Node API server   — /api/worlds/* (publishing + gallery)
#        * HTTP on API_PORT
#        * Optionally serves the SPA bundle when SERVE_STATIC is set
#
#   3. Vite-built SPA    — static files in client/dist/
#        * Served by the Node API server (SERVE_STATIC=1) OR by nginx
#
# `make dev`   runs 1+2 alongside Vite's dev server.
# `make build` builds all three artifacts.
# `make start` runs 1+2 against the built artifacts, with the API process
#              also serving the SPA so one port carries the full web surface.
# `docs/SELF_HOSTING.md` covers nginx + TLS + systemd.

# =============================================================================
# Rust game server
# =============================================================================

# TCP port for HTTP fallback, /session-config, /ws/, /healthz.
BIND_ADDR=0.0.0.0:4001

# Older SpacetimeDB integration toggle — leave as-is unless you know better.
SKIP_SPACETIMEDB_VERIFY=1

# Dev proxy hints: Vite forwards /ws, /session-config, /healthz to this
# address when you run `make dev`. Not used in production.
SERVER_PORT=4001
SERVER_HOST=localhost

# Optional override: when the SPA is served from a different origin than
# the game server (e.g. SPA on Vercel, game on a VPS) set this to the
# game server's public origin so the client can find it.
# VITE_MULTIPLAYER_HTTP_ORIGIN=https://game.example.com

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# WebTransport (QUIC/UDP) — used by the game client for packet-level netcode.
# This port must be reachable directly from the browser. nginx CANNOT
# reverse-proxy it (HTTP/3-over-QUIC over UDP). Open the UDP port in your
# firewall / security group and, if needed, put WT_PUBLIC_URL on a different
# hostname than the SPA.

WT_BIND_ADDR=0.0.0.0:4002
WT_HOST=127.0.0.1

# Public URL returned by /session-config. Set this when the port or hostname
# the browser hits differs from WT_BIND_ADDR (e.g. behind a NAT / forwarder).
# WT_PUBLIC_URL=https://wt.example.com:4002

# Production: point these at your CA-signed cert files. The Rust server
# loads them directly; no need to pre-terminate TLS. In dev they're left
# unset and a self-signed cert is generated and hash-pinned in the browser.
# WT_CERT_PEM=/etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/fullchain.pem
# WT_KEY_PEM=/etc/letsencrypt/live/yourdomain.com/privkey.pem

# =============================================================================
# Node API server (npm run api:dev / api:start)
# =============================================================================
# Hosts /api/worlds/* — publish, gallery listing, screenshots. Same code
# that runs on Vercel; api/server.ts mounts each handler at its Vercel URL.

# Port and bind address for the API. Keep on 127.0.0.1 behind nginx; use
# 0.0.0.0 only if the process is the edge-facing server.
API_PORT=3000
API_HOST=127.0.0.1

# When set, the API process also serves the SPA bundle with correct cache
# headers (immutable /assets/*, revalidated HTML) and SPA fallback. Use
# this for single-box deployments without nginx, or for `vite preview`-
# style local production smoke tests.
#
#   unset / 0 / false  -> API only (nginx serves client/dist separately)
#   1 / true           -> serve ../client/dist
#   /abs/path          -> serve that directory
#
# `make start` defaults this to 1 so one command brings up the whole stack.
# SERVE_STATIC=1

# =============================================================================
# Vite dev server (make dev only)
# =============================================================================

ALLOWED_HOSTS=localhost
CLIENT_PORT=5555

# =============================================================================
# World publishing + /gallery storage
# =============================================================================
# Enables the "Publish to Cloud" button in the world builder and the
# /gallery feed. Pick ONE backend — leave both unset to hide the feature
# without breaking anything else.

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Backend A: local filesystem (simplest)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Stores worlds + screenshots under a directory on the API server. No
# external service required. Takes precedence over R2 when both are set.
# Recommended for single-box self-hosted deployments.
#
# WORLDS_STORAGE_DIR=/var/lib/vibe-land-worlds

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Backend B1: Cloudflare R2 (production)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Set all four variables. The client uploads directly to R2 via presigned
# PUT URLs, so the API function never handles the bytes.
#
# IMPORTANT: the R2 bucket needs CORS. Cloudflare dashboard → R2 →
# your bucket → Settings → CORS Policy:
#
#   [{"AllowedOrigins":["*"],"AllowedMethods":["GET","PUT","HEAD"],
#     "AllowedHeaders":["*"],"ExposeHeaders":["ETag"],"MaxAgeSeconds":3600}]
#
# Without this, browser uploads fail with "No 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin'".
#
# R2_ACCOUNT_ID=
# R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID=
# R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=
# R2_BUCKET=
#
# Optional: a public CDN domain mapped to the R2 bucket (Cloudflare custom
# domain). When set the client reads world JSON + screenshots straight
# from the CDN instead of going through /api/worlds/<id>, which offloads
# large reads and gets free edge caching.
#
# R2_PUBLIC_URL=https://vibe-land-worlds.your-domain.com

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Backend B2: local MinIO via docker-compose (R2 emulator for dev)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Run `npm run r2:up` to start an S3-compatible server on localhost:9000
# with a preset bucket. Leave R2_ACCOUNT_ID unset so the code uses
# R2_ENDPOINT explicitly.
#
# R2_ENDPOINT=http://localhost:9000
# R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID=minioadmin
# R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=minioadmin
# R2_BUCKET=vibe-land-dev
# R2_REGION=us-east-1
# R2_FORCE_PATH_STYLE=1
